                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Nested Notes Collapsible -->
                    <details class="notes-box">
                        <summary>
                            <h4>
                                <span><i class="fa-solid fa-lightbulb"></i> Notes & Guidance</span>
                                <i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down toggle-icon"></i>
                            </h4>
                        </summary>
                        <div class="notes-content">
                            <ul>
                                <li><strong>Packet Structure:</strong>
                                    <ul>
                                        <li><em>Header:</em> Contains destination address, packet number, and
                                            originator's address.</li>
                                        <li><em>Payload:</em> The actual data being sent.</li>
                                        <li><em>Trailer:</em> End of packet marker and error checking data.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </li>
                                <li><strong>Packet Switching:</strong>
                                    <ul>
                                        <li>Data is broken into packets.</li>
                                        <li>Each packet may take a different route through the network.</li>
                                        <li>A <strong>router</strong> controls the route a packet takes.</li>
                                        <li>Packets may arrive out of order and must be reordered upon arrival.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </li>
                                <li><strong>Transmission Terminology:</strong>
                                    <ul>
                                        <li><em>Serial:</em> One bit at a time over a single wire (reliable over long
                                            distances).</li>
                                        <li><em>Parallel:</em> Multiple bits simultaneously over multiple wires (faster
                                            but prone to interference/skew over long distances).</li>
                                        <li><em>Simplex:</em> One direction only (e.g., radio broadcast).</li>
                                        <li><em>Half-duplex:</em> Both directions, but not at the same time (e.g.,
                                            walkie-talkie).</li>
                                        <li><em>Full-duplex:</em> Both directions simultaneously (e.g., telephone call).
                                        </li>
                                    </ul>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </details>
                </div>
            </details>

